rnwall)."],"variants":[{"name":"Trevillion","meanings":["Cornish: variant of   Trevillian  ."]},{"name":"Trevallion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevillian","meanings":["Cornish: variant of <b>Trevelyan</b>, a habitational name from Trevelyan in Saint Veep (Cornwall). The placename derives from Middle Cornish <i>tre(f)</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + either an unrecorded Old Cornish personal name equivalent either to Old Breton <i>Ilian</i> or the recorded Old Cornish <i>Milian</i>, with mutation of <i>m</i> to <i>v</i>. This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland. Compare   Trovillion  ."]},{"name":"Trevillyan","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevelyn","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevalion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevelion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Henry Tre